name: Decision Maker Lead Finder
description:
Find the key decision-makers you need, fast.

This agent identifies business owners or CEOs of local companies in any area you choose. Simply enter what kind of businesses you’re looking for and where, and it will:

* Search the area and gather public information
* Return names, roles, and contact details when available
* Provide smart Google search suggestions if details aren’t found

Perfect for:

* B2B sales teams seeking verified leads
* Recruiters sourcing local talent
* Researchers looking to connect with business leaders

Save hours of manual searching and get straight to the people who matter most.
instructions:
Input the type of businesses that you'd like to contact and a target location and the agent will find you leads.

Start off with a small number and increase the search results once you're happy.

input_default.text: Here we do the initial google search to get back the results

input_default.name: Location
input_default.description: Enter a specific location (e.g. city, neighborhood, or address). For example: “San Francisco”, “Palo Alto”, or “SoHo, NYC”. This helps narrow the search to a specific area.

input_default.name: Search Radius (meters, max 50,000)
input_default.description: Defines how far around the specified location we’ll look for businesses. For example, 5000 meters covers a large neighborhood or small city.

input_default.name: Max Number of Businesses to Analyze (max 60)
input_default.description: The maximum number of businesses the agent will analyze from the search results. We’ll attempt to identify the CEO or owner for each one.

input_default.name: Business Type
input_default.description: Describe the kind of businesses you're targeting. For example: “AI startups”, “digital marketing agencies”, or “coffee roasters”. This will be used in a Google Maps search.

sub_graphs.name: Find Business CEO
sub_graphs.description: Input info on a business, this agent will find it's CEO / Leader for you.

input_default.prompt:
You are a business CEO/Leader identifier. 

Your task is to identify the CEO/Leader of the business below by conducting web research. In order to identify the CEO, use your web search tool.  

Here is the business to find the CEO of:
<business_info> 
{{BUSINESS_INFO}} 
</business_info>  


Once you can confidently identify the business owner or CEO based on the search results, provide the details in the following format in your "finished" message (no tool call).
<identified_owner_ceo> 
Name: [Owner's or CEO's full name] 
Position: [Owner or CEO] 
Business Name: [Name of the business] 
Email: [Owner's or CEO's email address, if available] 
Phone Number: [Owner's or CEO's phone number, if available] 
Business Address: [Complete business address] 
</identified_owner_ceo>

Only include the fields for which you have information from the search results. 
Do not make assumptions or add information that is not explicitly stated.  

If you cannot yet confidently identify the business owner or CEO, use your web search tool to find more information about the business owner or CEO. 

When creating these search queries: 
1. Use specific details from the business information provided 
2. Focus on finding the owner's or CEO's identity and contact information 
3. Vary the types of searches (e.g., business name + CEO, business address + proprietor, written questions also work well etc.) 
4. Include location-specific searches if applicable 
5. Consider searching for business registration or public records 
6. Aim to uncover the owner's or CEO's contact details (email, phone number) if possible  

Remember: 
1. Never make assumptions when identifying the business, owner or CEO. 
2. If any piece of required information is missing, do not try to fill it in with guesses, never make assumptions
3. Be certain of the owner's or CEO's identity before providing an <identified_owner_ceo> response. 
4. Always call a tool, if you provide a message without a tool call or a "finished" message, this will be taken as your final answer.

Analyze the business information now and provide your response accordingly.
input_default.sys_prompt: Thinking carefully step by step decide which function to call. Always choose a function call from the list of function signatures, and always provide the complete argument provided with the type matching the required jsonschema signature, no missing argument is allowed. If you have already completed the task objective, you can end the task by providing the end result of your work as a finish message. Function parameters that has no default value and not optional typed has to be provided.
